{"/service/ndnp/ak/batch_ak_chinooksalmon_ver03/data/sn84020662/00414185940/1949042901/1196.xml":{"full_text":"THE NOME NUGGET\nPublished Monday, Wednesday and Friday by the\nNOME PUBLISHING CO.\nNOME, ALASKA\nTelephone: Main 125 P. O. Box 6ia\n$1.50 PER MONTH $16.00 A YEAR\nW. A. Boucher ....Owner-Publisher\nEntered as second class matter October 14. 1943, at the postoffice\nat Nome, Alaska, under the Act of March 3, 1879.\nNome, Alaska, Friday, April 29, 1949\nTHE WORLD NEEDS FREE TRADE\nWhen the Thirteen Colonies won their independence\nfrom Britain, they represented thirteen independent\nand sovereign States. Each colony issued its own money\nand had the right to set up tariffs to prevent the sale of\nthe products of all the other colonies inside its domain.\nThe money issued by each colony was ol dubious value\nin the other colonies and, consequently, hampered the\ndevelopment of economic intercourse between the peo\nples of the colonies.\nIf that condition had continued, after the formation\nof the Federal Union, there would have been no devel\nopment of the economy of this Continent to compare\nwith what the years have produced. Instead of a manu\nfacturer in one state being able to ship his products:\nfreely to a buyer in other states, there would have been j\nquestions of currency valuation and exchange, in addi\ntion to possible prohibitory tariffs, to prevent such busi\nness.\nNow, if we glance away from our own continent and;\nlook into the Western part of Europe, we find a group j\nof nations operating economically as the colonies did\nbefore the Union was formed. This means, for example,\nthat if a manufacturer in Belgium wants to sell some\ngoods in France, he must not only pay the tariff levied\nagainst his products, but he must arrange some method\nof collecting the amount due him for his goods.\nNaturally, he cannot accept French currency unless\nhe wants to buy something in France, because, obvious- i\niy, it is not usable in Belgium. If the manufacturer does\nnot want to buy in France, he must require the French j\npurchaser to pay him in the money of a third country,\nwhich, under present conditions, is usually the dollar or'\nthe pound.\nIt is not surprising that trade between the European\ncountres lags far behind that between the forty-eight\nStates of the American Union. Likewise, the economic\ndevelopment of the European area does not compare\nwith that which took place on the American continent.\nThe full answer may not be found in tariffs and cur\nrency barriers, but many economists and political stu\ndents are convinced that much of the blame for a retard\ned economy is to be assessed against these factors.\nRecently, Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg\nformed a customs union so that they could exchange\ntheir goods without any money difficulties. Now, an ef\nfort is being made to extend the boundaries of the union\nso that France and Western Germany may be included.\nThe idea is sound and should be broadened to include\nmost of the nations in Western Europe. In fact, it should\nbe gradually extended to include all the nations of the\nearth.\nThere is, we think, a lesson for the United States to\nlearn in the history of its own development and the les\nser development of other areas. We set the world an\nexample by establishing high tariffs, which led to quota\nrestrictions, currency controls and other barriers to\nworld trade. Now, we are suggesting to the Western na\ntions of Europe that they act to permit the unimpeded\nflow of trade between them and, if we are logical, we\nmust be ready to assist in the development of the\nworld\u2019s economy by joining in the effort to facilitate the\nswapping of goods and services between all peoples.\nThose who oppose the removal of tariffs and other\ntrade barriers generally fear that such removal will in\njure their business. This might conceivably be the re\nsult in certain instances, but what the business men\noverlook is the prospect that a greater flow of interna\ntional trade will permit them to make more profits than\nthey now get through the operation of tariffs, currency\ncontrols and other hampering barriers that stop the\nflow of commerce.\nHARD TO BELIEVE I\nmM\nEDUCATION\u2019S TASK TODAY\n(New World News Service)\nCommunism has forced us to rethink every area of\nour national life, whether we like it or not.\nGeorge E. Sokolsky, national syndicated columnist,!\nwrote in an article on April: \u201cMilitant, undemocratc\nideologies have gained power out of all proportion to(\ntheir numbers because their proponents have been skill\nfully educated in their principles and doctrines based on\nclass and race warfare.\u201d Td meet this challenge he told\nof the amazing steps the Los Angeles Board of Educa\ntion have taken and quoted a paragraph from their\nstatement of policy: \u201cThe schools of the democratic na\ntions must, therefore, teach their future leaders the\ndemocratic point of view which is based on moral and j\nspiritual concepts. We look to our educators to teach\nthe simple basic principles of A. sound moral standards, j\nB. faith in God, C. respect for human dignity.\u201d Conclud- j\ning his column Sokolsky said, \u201cLos Angeles has shown\nthe way.\u201d\nA few days later a California school principal spoke\nat a conference on \u201cEducation\u2019s part in this ideological;\nage\u201d held at Moral Re-Armament\u2019s headquarters in Los j\nAngeles. \u201cThe function of education in an ideological'\nage is to train men and women to step out of the class\nroom into the heart of the nation to answer its needs,\u201d,\nhe declared. One teacher brought four of her pupils as I\n\u201cvisual aids.\u201d For the past six months she has been;\nteaching 300 high school students each day not only the j\nideas of democracy, but how they can be applied at'\nhome and school.\nA university professor described the vicious battle\nfor control raging on his campus, and then introduced\ntwo of her students, a former big league baseball player\nand his wife. \u201cMy professor has given me an ideology,\nfighting spirit, and a reason why there should, be a liv\ning democracy,\u201d said this student. He told how their\nclass had found \u201ca positive working basis\u201d rather than\nbeing bogged down by \u201cparalysis of analysis.\u201d When\nhis wife, a first grade teacher, introduced the idea of\nabsolute moral standards into the class room, parents\ncalled her up to inquire what had caused their children\nto behave so differently at home. j\nThese are the men and women who in and out of the!\nclass room are answering the nation\u2019s needs.\nOne comforting feature of the big appropriation to j\nmeet the 1949-50 federal budget, says the Dillon, S. C.,i\nHerald, is that it will be a bulwark against deflation, j\nThese are extraordinary times and extraordinary mea-l\nsures are necessary to meet them. U. S. cannot afford a\ndepression or even a recession until the world recovers,\nits balance. If the nation slides into a depression, the bil\nlions we have poured into other countries will have been\nwasted and Communism will spread like wildfire. In\nother words, we are playing a game in which the stakes\nare high and if we lay down our hand the pot is lost. The\nhigher the ante goes, however, the more we should'\nstrive to economize at home.\nCHURCHES\nCATHOLIC CHURCH\nSunday\u2014\n8:00 a.m.\u2014Mass\n9:30 a.m.\u2014Mass.\n4:30 p.m.\u2014At the Base Chapel.\nLAVINIA WALLACE YOUNG\nMISSION\nPastors Rev. H. R. Amundsen\nand Rev. Theran McGrew\nSunday:\n11:00 a.m. Sunday School.\n7:30 p.m. Evening Service.\nWednesday 3:30 p.m. Chil\ndren\u2019s Miracle Book Club.\nThursday 7:30 p.m. Prayer\nMeeting.\nFEDERATED CHURCH\nSunday, 10:00 a.m. Sunday School\nPENTACOSTAL ASSEMBLY OF\nGOD\nThird Avenue West\nMiss H. E. Brown\nMissionary in Charge\nMay 1, 1949, is Missionary Sunday\nSunday\u2014\nSunday School. 10:00 a.m.\nAdult Bible Class.11:00 a.m.\nEvening Service 7:30 p.m.\nTuesday\u2014\nYoung Peoples Meeting 4:00 p.m.\nWednesday\u2014\nBible Study .7:30 p.m.\nFriday\u2014\nBible Study and\nPrayer Meeting .7:00 p.m.\nEVERYONE WELCOME\nCHURCH OF THE NAZARENE\nThird and Division\nPastor\u2014Lewis I. Hudgins\n\u201cIt is-well to let a little sunshine\nout as well as in.\u201d\n10:00 a.m. Singspiration and Sun\na\nday School classes.\n11:00 a.m. Morning message.\n7:00 p.m. Young People\u2019s Meeting.\n7:30 p.m. Singspiration and special\nmusic.\n8:00 p.m. Evening message.\nWednesday: 7:30 p.m. Melody and\nPrayer.\nCome and bring your Bible.\nYou are ever welcome to attend\nthese services.\nNOME GOSPEL MISSION\nof\nAlaska Evangelisation Society\nRev. Vern Riraling. Pastor\n\nSunday:\n2:00 p.m. Sunday School for\nboys and girls.\nPreaching service in the Esklm*\nlanguage by James Savok.\n7:30 p.m. Gospel Service.\nTuesday:\n7:30 p.m. Prayer and Testimony\nThursday:\n2:00 to 4:00 p.m. Bible Club for\nBoys and Girls.\nFriday:\n7:3Q pjn. Bible Study.\nf K.K.\nPublic Library\n\u2018f\nv Open\nv\nFridays\u20147:30 to 9:00 P.M.\n\nSaturdays\u20142:30 to 4:00 P.M.","height":"27604","width":"20024"}}
